label chapter10:

    # [Scene: Rooftop Community Garden / Evacuation Shelter | Dusk]

    scene bg ch10_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Soft, hopeful piano under a rising synth pad]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls, the soft tick of settling metal, occasional murmur of voices from below]
    "You remember the choice like a hinge: not surrender to the wall, not an uncompromising shutout of outsiders, but a promise to bind voices together. Tonight the promise is a color—yellow sticky notes, hand-lettered placards, the"
    "warm filament of bulbs that makes the wet soil look like a dark, familiar loam. Marina moves with an organizer’s speed, tying an extra string of lights while talking ten to the dozen; the children from"
    "her afterschool program weave between the beds, fingers smudged with compost and ink from petition signatures."
    "Your chest loosens a little. The rooftop smells of damp earth and citrus oil—someone's hand sanitizer or a jar of lemon peels for composting—and it smells like possibility. Your pendant hums with a faint solar charge"
    "against your collarbone. You leave it lit sometimes on purpose; the small circle of glow feels like a signal you can hold onto when the rest of the world requires more than you think you have."

    scene bg ch10_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The tap of a tablet screen; the murmur of a video call settling into place]
    show marina_lopez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "Look at this—signatures from the school, the fishermen's co-op, three local bakers, and half a classroom of kids who drew storm maps.' She laughs, breathless. 'They drew the marsh like a sleeping dragon. You should see it."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "A sleeping dragon we can't afford to chop up.' You slide a pamphlet into the clasp of the board, thumb catching on your notebook at your hip. (Quiet) 'We stitch the science to the story. We make the court of public opinion too loud to ignore."

    marina_lopez "And Elias—will his endorsements sit on the board or be a footnote?"

    amina_reyes "He wants to help. We make sure what he brings doesn't drown out the people who live here.' Your voice is steady but not species of steel; there is warmth in it that feels like a rope thrown to someone across a channel. 'We need his numbers up front, not as a frosting over decisions made elsewhere."
    hide marina_lopez
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch10_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Elias's footsteps, slight hiss of damp fabric]
    show elias_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "You convinced me to bring the endorsements earlier than I planned.' He gestures to his tablet; the screen casts cool light across his face. 'If this is going to be policy-ready, regional funders will need proof you can point to. Dr. Sato's sequences give us a decade of projections where living shorelines buy the town time and reduce extreme surge amplification."

    "Dr. Sato" "Not all of it. It is a projection, and projections are arguments dressed in numbers. We can show variability, confidence intervals—' He fingers a graph. '—but the story you tell will be what gets people to read beyond the headline."
    show niko_kaur at right:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "Which is why we bring a patched boat and a living breakwater to the square. Let them see it hold water without needing a spreadsheet to believe in it.' There’s steel under the humor; he pins his gaze on you. 'We build the first test in public. Let people touch the kelp mats, see the kids plant the cordgrass. Tangibility beats talk every time."
    "The conversation slides between technical terms and tactile plans, and each voice reshapes the rooftop into a workshop of ideas. You keep picturing the boardwalk—its peeling boards, the market stalls—but tonight those images are distant enough to be useful: calibrations rather than wounds."
    hide elias_hart
    hide niko_kaur

    scene bg ch10_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The piano swells into a gentle, ascending motif]
    "You unroll a map from your notebook and spread it across a crate-turned-table. It is dense with margin notes—tide observations, locations for pilot installations, a list of contacts for legal aid. Dr. Sato leans in, pointing"
    "out a set of nodes where marsh restoration could both absorb surge and preserve key fishing channels."

    "Dr. Sato" "If you place living-break substructures along these contours, the sediment retention profile improves. Pair it with targeted, hardened low walls at core infrastructure points and you have a hybrid solution that is defensible in both legal and engineering reviews."
    show amina_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "Defensible—yes. But also legible. If the people can't see the logic, they will call it a compromise for someone else.' You tap a location by the old boatyard. 'We need demonstration that keeps livelihoods intact."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "We can frame it as phased implementation. Start small—a pilot that can be evaluated, scaled if successful. Funders like scaleable metrics. I don't like the sound of the word 'instrumentalization,' but transparency will be how we avoid it."
    show niko_kaur at center:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "And who decides success, Elias? The spreadsheet, or the people who fish at dawn?"

    elias_hart "Both. The metrics inform the people, the people's experience informs the metrics. We make the process iterative and public. That way the people own its steps."
    "There is a pause like the breath someone takes before a push. You feel the corner of your mouth lift—relief from seeing the adults find a sentence to stand on. The rooftop hums; even the solar panels sound like soft applause in the breeze."

    menu:
        "Lead with data-heavy presentations":
            "You clear your throat and outline a schedule for technical briefings, inviting funders to the first week. It's effective: engineers nod, some regional reps lean forward. But a few neighbors exchange puzzled looks—this may look too 'expert-driven' to folk who want to see their hands in the mud."
        "Open with stories from the market and the marsh":
            "You hand the mic to Marina and a fisherman first. The crowd leans in; faces soften. People clap for the vivid stories. Later, Elias' graphs slot into the narrative like proofs appended to testimony, which wins supporters who needed a human reason to read the numbers."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both approaches are acknowledged; the scene continues with Marina's remark and the rooftop's combined strategy."
    "Marina: (after the choice, grinning) 'Both styles have their charm. But tonight—' She sweeps a hand across the rooftop. '—we do both. Stories first, numbers to anchor them. People hear their neighbors before they hear the models.'"
    "Amina Reyes: (thinking) Both. Of course both. It is always both."
    hide amina_reyes
    hide elias_hart
    hide niko_kaur

    scene bg ch10_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rustle of pamphlets, a child's laughter, distant honk of a delivery truck]
    "Outside volunteers arrive in clusters—students with cameras, an activist from a coastal NGO with a clipboard, a regional legislator's aide with a polite, curious expression. The coalition's beehive widens. You watch as Elias Hart speaks one-on-one"
    "with a regional funder who has come quietly to listen; Dr. Sato calibrates his presentation for a policy briefing; Niko Kaur organizes a weekend build day and argues with the contractor over reclaimed timber."
    "A woman from the NGO pulls you aside, earnest and quick. 'There's traction,' she says. 'We can amplify this—media, a petition platform, maybe a televised town hall. But they'll want a hero story, a simple narrative. Are you ready for that?'"
    show amina_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "A simple narrative that still holds complexity.' You say aloud the impossible sentence. 'We will not let our message be simplified into a promise that erases the marsh. We will not let 'jobs' become a synonym for 'sell-out.'"
    "She studies you—young, yet steadier than her features predict. 'That's risky. Simpler stories travel farther.'"

    amina_reyes "Then we make the story memorable and messy in the same breath. Show the pilot. Show the scientists. Show the boatwrights. Let people see how the compromise is not surrender but weaving."
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch10_453e40_6 at full_bg
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "People touch wood. They remember how a hull feels under their palms. Bring them a piece to hold—let them feel the compromise is still hand-made."
    show elias_hart at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "We have a tentative meeting with a developer rep tomorrow—plausible capital, and the chance to scale the pilot. It could get us the funding to expand.' He looks at you; for a moment he is unadorned by office armor. 'But I want your read before I give them a time."
    "You consider the developer's pitch in light of the rooftop's warm light and the children's grubby hands. There is opportunity there—money, scale—but you remember Dr. Sato's warning about arguments dressed as numbers and Marina's note about hero narratives. Compromise will require edges."

    menu:
        "Agree to meet the developer, but insist on public terms":
            "You tell Elias to schedule the meeting but make it public and conditional: any terms discussed must be presented at the town hall. Elias nods, relieved; the funder smiles at the transparency, and Marina files the time into a public calendar. It feels like taking on a guinea pig—dangerous, but accountable."
        "Delay the meeting until the pilot proves itself":
            "You ask Elias to stall—no private talks until the pilot shows measurable outcomes. Elias frowns, worried about losing momentum, but accepts. Niko claps your shoulder; there's relief in his posture, but some funders pull away when they hear the timeline. Momentum slows, but the movement's heart beats clearer."

    # --- merge ---
    "Both choices lead back into the rooftop's ongoing planning and the drafting of the Mosaic Charter."
    show marina_lopez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "Either path makes us wiser in different ways. Public scrutiny will raise the stakes; delay will test our patience. Both are risks."
    hide niko_kaur
    show amina_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "We will not be swallowed by the swell. We set the rules."
    hide elias_hart
    hide marina_lopez
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch10_453e40_7 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The rooftop applauds; the sound is raw and immediate]
    "Night becomes plans. You spend it pinning together legal contacts and media lists, printing flyers with graphs sharpened by Dr. Sato into data that sings. Elias Hart teaches a half-hour primer on how to read a"
    "confidence interval to a circle of older fishermen. Niko Kaur brings out samples of cordgrass and demonstrates tying a mat together with kids watching with solemn curiosity."
    "At one point you step back and look at the rooftop: a constellation of hands and faces under warm bulbs, a stitched patchwork of science, craft, and memory. The city below glows like a map of choices, and for the first time in a long while the map feels writable."

    scene bg ch10_453e40_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The ascending motif grows, brass hinting at an exhale]
    "Someone brings up the danger you all tacitly invited—the money that comes with strings. A man with a polished voice and a prosperous tie could turn the pilot into a showcase for his own portfolio. You"
    "feel the old fear—Marisol used to bend for such men—but tonight you also feel a network: signatures, kids' drawings, tweets from activists, procedural transparency pledged on the notice board."
    show elias_hart at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_hart "If the legislator shows, it'll change the conversation. He can bring funding and legitimacy. But he will want a neat commit. We'll need to set boundaries."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "We write the boundaries first. We tell them what this pilot will and will not be. We make the town's needs non-negotiable."
    show marina_lopez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "Draft the charter.' She grins, eyes bright. 'We make a living document: the Mosaic Charter—named for how small pieces can make a whole image."
    "You like the name. Mosaic implies pieces, hands, and the deliberate act of placing. It implies repair that honors the image, not erasure."
    hide elias_hart
    hide amina_reyes
    hide marina_lopez

    scene bg ch10_453e40_9 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The soft creak of crates; distant gulls waking]
    "You sit on a crate and breathe the cold salt air into your lungs. The pendant at your throat finally goes dark as the solar charge drains beneath the clouds. You close your eyes and imagine"
    "a path forward—pilot sites, living beds, targeted defenses where absolutely necessary, legal language that protects the marsh, jobs that don't chew it up. The plan feels not inevitable but possible."
    "Your thoughts do not coast on certainty; they ache with the knowledge of danger and the memory of loss. But tonight the ache has purpose. You are not alone."

    scene bg ch10_453e40_10 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano resolves on an open, expectant chord]
    "You stand, fingers smelling faintly of compost and sea salt, and pin the draft of the Mosaic Charter to the board with a nail from Niko's multi-tool. The paper flutters, a small flag for a long campaign."
    "You can feel the momentum. Outside activists will marshal resources; a regional legislator may come bearing promises ; developers will circle, promising jobs and speed. You will have to choose how to use what comes without"
    "letting the town become an exhibit for someone else's ambitions. But that is tomorrow's work."
    "For now there is a rooftop, a charter, and a beehive of people who have asked to be joined."
    "You breathe, and that breath carries a tide of hope."

    scene bg ch10_453e40_11 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle swell into a single sustained tone]
    "You step to the edge and look out over the marsh—its dark silhouette a promise and a demand. The city hums beneath you; the campaign hums beside you. You feel the moment as a hinge again, but this hinge swings upward."
    "A page must turn."

    scene bg ch10_453e40_12 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    jump chapter11
    return
